The problem involves finding the number of anti-palindromes in base 3 less than \(3^{12}\) with no two consecutive equal digits, using that count to define \(k\), and then solving a circle problem based on \(k-18\). An anti-palindrome satisfies \(a_i + a_{n-i} = 2\) for all digits in its base-3 representation, along with the constraint that no two consecutive digits are equal. The count of such numbers with up to 12 digits is computed recursively, yielding \(b_1 = 126\). Then \(k = b_1 + 27 = 153\), so \(k-18 = 135\). For 135 numbers arranged around a circle where each number is one more than the gcd of its neighbors, the numbers must be either 2 or 3 in a repeating pattern, giving a sum of \(7 \times 135 / 3 = 315\).

